<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-742-816  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 742 816.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Which Computer?andP;  April 1989 p13(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What's up with Amstrad? (Amstrad Inc's profits drop)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brake, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Amstrad Inc's profits dropped during the last half of 1988,primarily due to some flaws in Amstrad's 2086 PC, problems withsupply of audio components from Taiwan and difficulties insupplying satellite dishes in quantity.andP;  Profits dropped 16percent to 75.3 million pounds sterling and Amstrad Chmn AlanSugar predicts that its 1988-1989 FY would be disastrous.andO;Amstrad's reputation has been damaged because its more powerfulmachines, those based on the 80286 and 80386 chips, are in shortsupply.andP;  In addition, Amstrad 2086s shipped before Jan 18, 1988,contain a flaw which makes it possible for the machine's hard diskto be erased without warning.andP;  Amstrad is also facing problemsfrom overseas, where the parent company of its trading partner,Corvus, has filed chapter 11 papers, often a prelude tobankruptcy.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Amstrad Inc. (earnings)Corvus Systems Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    CRVSQ.andO;Product:   Amstrad PC2086 (microcomputer) (marketing).andO;Topic:     Trade ShowsMarketingProfitFinancial StabilitySystem Integrity.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Alan Sugar. (portrait)Person:    Sugar, Alan (management).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>